==English==
[[Image:PWN Encyclopedia.jpg|thumb|right|The National Scientific Publishers encyclopedia (Polish)]]

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|encyclopaedia||Britain}}
* {{alter|en|encyclopædia||archaic}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*peh₂w-}}
From {{bor|en|NL.|encyclopaedia|t=general education}}, from Renaissance {{der|en|grc|ἐγκυκλοπαιδεία|t=education in the circle of arts and sciences}}, a mistaken [[univerbation|univerbated]] form of {{der|en|grc-koi|ἐγκύκλιος παιδείᾱ|t=education in the circle of arts and sciences}}, from {{m|grc|ἐγκύκλιος|t=circular}} + {{m|grc|παιδείᾱ|t=child-rearing, education}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|Canada}} {{IPA|en|/ənˌsəɪ.kləˈpi.di.ə/}}
* {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|en|/ɪnˌsaɪ.kləˈpi(ː).di.ə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-encyclopedia.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|iːdiə|s=6}}
* {{hyphenation|en|en|cy|clo|pe|di|a}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|encyclopediae|encyclopediæ}}

# A [[comprehensive]] [[reference work]] (often spanning several printed volumes) with articles (usually arranged in alphabetical order, or sometimes arranged by category) on a range of [[subjects]], sometimes general, sometimes limited to a particular field.
#: {{ux|en|I only use the library for the '''encyclopedia''', as we’ve got most other books here.}}
#: {{ux|en|His life's work as a four-volume '''encyclopedia''' of aviation topics.}}
# {{lb|en|dated}} The [[circle]] of [[arts]] and [[sciences]]; a [[comprehensive]] summary of [[knowledge]], or of a branch of [[knowledge]].

====Usage notes====
The spelling ''encyclopedia'' is standard in American English, preferred in Canadian English, accepted in Australian and International English, and also very common in British English. It is more common than ''encyclopaedia'', for example, in UK newspapers on Google News in 2009 by a 7:3 margin.

