==English==

===Etymology 1===
[[File:Runic letter ansuz.png|left|30px|Runic letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚫ|sc=Runr|tr=a|t=ansuz}}, source for Anglo-Saxon Futhorc letters replaced by ''a'']]
From {{inh-lite|en|enm|-}} and {{inh-lite|en|ang|-}} lower case letter {{m-lite|enm|a}} and split of {{inh-lite|en|enm|-}} and {{der-lite|en|ang|-}} lower case letter {{m-lite|enm|æ}}.
:* [[File:Rune-Ac.png|10px|Anglo-Saxon Futhorc letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚪ|sc=Runr|tr=a|t=āc}}]] {{der-lite|en|ang|-}} lower case letter {{m-lite|enm|a}} from 7th century replacement by Latin lower case letter {{m-lite|la|a}} of the Anglo-Saxon Futhorc letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚪ|tr=a|t=āc|sc=Runr}}, derived from Runic letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚫ|tr=a|t=Ansuz|sc=Runr}}.
:* [[File:Rune-Æsc.png|10px|Anglo-Saxon Futhorc letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚫ|sc=Runr|tr=æ|æsc}}]] {{der-lite|en|ang|-}} lower case letter {{m-lite|enm|æ}} from 7th century replacement by Latin lower case ligature {{m-lite|la|æ}} of the Anglo-Saxon Futhorc letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚫ|t=æsc|sc=Runr|tr=æ}}, also derived from Runic letter {{m-lite|mul|ᚫ|t=Ansuz|tr=a|sc=Runr}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{l-lite|en|·}} {{q-lite|[[Gregg Shorthand]]}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{q-lite|letter name}}
** {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ˈeɪ/}}
** {{audio|en|en-us-a.ogg|Audio (US)}}
** {{a|AusE}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ˈæɪ/}}
** {{rhymes-lite|en|eɪ|s=1}}
*: The current pronunciation resulted from the [[w:Great Vowel Shift|Great Vowel Shift]]. Before the early part of the 17th century, the pronunciation was similar to that in other languages.
* {{q-lite|phoneme}} {{IPA-lite|en|/æ/|/ɑː/|/eɪ/}}, etc.

====Letter====
{{head-lite|en|letters|lowercase||uppercase|A|plural|as|or|a's|langname=English}}

# {{Latn-def-lite|en|letter|1|langname=English}}

=====Usage notes=====
* In English, the letter ''a'' usually denotes the [[w:near-open front unrounded vowel|near-open front unrounded vowel]] ({{IPA-lite|en|/æ/}}), as in ''[[pad]]'', the [[w:open back unrounded vowel|open back unrounded vowel]] ({{IPA-lite|en||/ɑː/}}) as in ''[[father]]'', or, followed by another vowel, the diphthong {{IPA-lite|en|/eɪ/}}, as in ''[[ace]]''.
* ''A'' is the third most common letter in English.

=====Derived terms=====
* Digraph sequences: [[ae]], [[ah]], [[ai]], [[au]], [[aw]], [[ay]], [[ea]], [[eau]], [[ia]], [[oa]], [[ua]]

=====See also=====
* (''Latin script letters'') '''[[letter]]'''; [[A]][[a]], [[B]][[b]], [[C]][[c]], [[D]][[d]], [[E]][[e]], [[F]][[f]], [[G]][[g]], [[H]][[h]], [[I]][[i]], [[J]][[j]], [[K]][[k]], [[L]][[l]], [[M]][[m]], [[N]][[n]], [[O]][[o]], [[P]][[p]], [[Q]][[q]], [[R]][[r]], [[S]][[s]], [[T]][[t]], [[U]][[u]], [[V]][[v]], [[W]][[w]], [[X]][[x]], [[Y]][[y]], [[Z]][[z]]

====Numeral====
{{head-lite|en|numeral symbols|lower case||upper case|A|langname=English|lemma=1}}

# {{ng-lite|The [[ordinal]] number '''[[first]]''', derived from this [[letter]] of the English [[alphabet]], called a and written in the [[Appendix:Latin script|Latin script]].}}

