===Etymology 2===
From {{inh-lite|en|enm|a}}, {{m-lite|enm|an}}, from {{inh-lite|en|ang|an|ān|t=one; a; lone; sole}}. The "n" was gradually lost before consonants in almost all dialects by the 15th century.

====Pronunciation====
* {{q-lite|stressed}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ˈeɪ/}}
* {{q-lite|unstressed}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-a-stressed.ogg|Audio (US), stressed}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-a-unstressed.ogg|Audio (US), unstressed}}
* {{rhymes-lite|en|eɪ|ə|s=1}}
* {{homophones|en|her}} {{q-lite|non-rhotic, unstressed}}

====Article====
{{head-lite|en|articles|indefinite|langname=English}}

# One; any indefinite example of; used to denote a singular item of a group. {{defdate|from before 1150}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux-lite|en|There was '''a''' man here looking for you yesterday.}}
#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae|volume=V|page=vii|text=With fresh material, taxonomic conclusions are leavened by recognition that the material examined reflects the site it occupied; '''a''' herbarium packet gives one only '''a''' small fraction of the data desirable for sound conclusions. Herbarium material does not, indeed, allow one to extrapolate safely: what you see is what you get{{...}}}}
#* '''2005''', Emily Kingsley (lyricist), Kevin Clash (voice actor), “A Cookie is a Sometime Food”, ''Sesame Street'', season 36, Sesame Workshop:
#*: ''Hoots the Owl:'' Yes a, fruit, is '''a''' {{SIC}}, any, time, food!
#* '''2016''', [https://web.archive.org/web/20170925022505/https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/lets-learn-english-lesson-4/3168920.html VOA Learning English] (public domain)
#*:  Anna, do you have a pen?  —  Yes. I have a pen in my bag. I have '''a''' (stressed) …
#*:: {{audio|en|Anna, do you have a pen.ogg|Audio (US)}}
# {{ng-lite|Used in conjunction with the adjectives score, dozen, hundred, thousand, and million, as a function word.}}
#: {{ux-lite|en|I've seen it happen '''a''' hundred times.}}
# One certain or particular; any single. {{defdate|from ca. 1150—1350}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, (2003)</ref>
#: {{ux-lite|en|We've received an interesting letter from '''a''' Mrs. Miggins of London.}}
# The same; one. {{defdate|16th Century}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux-lite|en|We are of '''a''' mind on matters of morals.}}
# [[any|Any]], [[every]]; used before a noun which has become modified to limit its scope;<ref name=WI3/> also used with a negative to indicate not a single one.<ref name=OCD>Lindberg, Christine A. (2007)</ref>
#: {{ux-lite|en|'''A''' man who dies intestate leaves his children troubles and difficulties.}}
#: {{ux-lite|en|He fell all that way, and hasn't '''a''' bump on his head?}}
# {{ng-lite|Used before plural nouns modified by few, good many, couple, great many, etc.}}
# Someone or something like; similar to;<ref name=OCD/> ''Used before a proper noun to create an example out of it.''
#: {{ux-lite|en|The center of the village was becoming '''a''' Times Square.}}

=====Usage notes=====
{{mainapp|English articles#Indefinite articles}}
* In standard English, the article ''a'' is used before consonant sounds, while ''[[an]]'' is used before vowel sounds; for more, see [[an#Usage_notes|''the usage notes about an'']].

=====Derived terms=====
* {{l-lite|en|a few}}
* {{l-lite|en|a great many}}

