==Galician==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh-lite|gl|la|ad||to, toward}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA-lite|gl|/a̝/}}

====Preposition====
{{head-lite|gl|prepositions|langname=Galician}}

# [[to]], [[toward]]; ''indicating direction of motion''
# {{ng-lite|introducing an [[indirect object]]}}
# {{ng-lite|used to indicate the [[time]] of an action}}
# {{lb|gl|with [[de]]}} [[to]], [[until]]; ''used to indicate the end of a [[range]]''
#: {{ux-lite|gl|de cinco '''a''' oito|from five '''to''' eight|inline=1}}
# [[by]], [[on]], by means of; ''expresses a mode of action''
#: {{ux-lite|gl|'''a''' pé|'''on''' foot|inline=1}}
# [[for]]; ''indicates [[price]] or [[cost]]''

=====Usage notes=====
The preposition ''a'' regularly forms contractions when it precedes the definite article {{m-lite|gl|o}}, {{m-lite|gl|a}}, {{m-lite|gl|os}}, and {{m-lite|gl|as}}. For example, ''a o'' ("to the") contracts to {{m-lite|gl|ao}} or {{m-lite|gl|ó}}, and ''a a'' ("to the") contracts to {{m-lite|gl|á}}.

=====Derived terms=====
{| class="wikitable"
|+ at/to + the table
|-
! - !! Singular !! Plural
|-
| Masculine || {{l-lite|gl|ao}} ({{l-lite|gl|ó}}) ||  {{l-lite|gl|aos}} ({{l-lite|gl|ós}})
|-
| Feminine|| {{l-lite|gl|á}}|| {{l-lite|gl|ás}}
|}

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh-lite|gl|roa-opt|a}}, from {{inh-lite|gl|la|illa}}, feminine of {{m-lite|la|ille||that}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA-lite|gl|/a̝/}}

====Article====
{{head-lite|gl|articles|g=f|masculine singular|o|feminine plural|as|masculine plural|os|langname=Galician}}

# {{lb|gl|definite}} [[the]]

=====Usage notes=====
The definite article {{m-lite|gl|o}} (in all its forms) regularly forms contractions when it follows the prepositions {{m-lite|gl|a||to}}, {{m-lite|gl|con||with}}, {{m-lite|gl|de||of, from}}, and {{m-lite|gl|en||in}}. For example, {{m-lite|gl||con a|with the}} contracts to {{m-lite|gl|coa}}, and {{m-lite|gl||en a|in the}} contracts to {{m-lite|gl|na}}.

Also, the definite article presents a second form that could be represented as <-lo/-la/-los/-las>, or either lack any specific representation. Its origin is in the assimilation of the last consonant of words ended in -s or -r, due to [[sandhi]], with the /l/ present in the article in pre-Galician-Portuguese period. So ''Vou comer o caldo'' or ''Vou come-lo caldo'' are representations of {{IPAchar-lite|/ˈβowˈkomelo̝ˈkaldo̝/}} ("I'm going to have my soup"). This phenomenon, rare in Portuguese, is already documented in 13th century Medieval Galician texts, as the ''{{w|Cantigas de Santa Maria}}''.<ref>{{cite-journal|last=Vaz Leão|first=Ângela|title=Questões de linguagem nas ''{{w|Cantigas de Santa Maria}}'', de Afonso X|journal=Scripta|date=2000|volume=4|issue=7|pages=11-24|doi=10.5752/P.2358-3428|url=http://periodicos.pucminas.br/index.php/scripta/article/view/10371/pdf|accessdate=16 November 2017}}</ref>

=====Derived terms=====
* {{l-lite|gl|á}}
* {{l-lite|gl|coa}}
* {{l-lite|gl|da}}
* {{l-lite|gl|na}}

===Etymology 3===

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA-lite|gl|/ˈa/}}

====Noun====
{{head-lite|gl|nouns|g=m|plural|as|langname=Galician}}

# [[a#English|a]] (name of the letter A, a)

===Etymology 4===
{{nonlemma}}

====Pronoun====
{{head-lite|gl|pronoun forms|langname=Galician}}

# {{inflection of|gl|ela||acc}}

===References===
<references/>

[[Category:gl:Latin letter names]]

