==Irish==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA-lite|ga|/ə/}}

===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ga|possessive pronoun}}
From {{inh-lite|ga|sga|a|a}}, from {{inh|ga|cel-pro|*esyo}} (the final vowel triggering lenition), feminine {{inh|ga|cel-pro|*esyās}} (the final ''-s'' triggering h-prothesis), plural {{inh|ga|cel-pro|*eysom}} (the final nasal triggering eclipsis), all from the genitive forms of {{der|ga|ine-pro|*éy}}. Cognate with {{cog-lite|cy|ei}}.

====Determiner====
{{head-lite|ga|determiners|cat2=possessive determiners|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|l}}}}

# [[his]], [[its]]
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' athair agus '''a''' mháthair|his father and mother}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Chaill an t-éan '''a''' chleití.|The bird lost its feathers.}}

====Determiner====
{{head-lite|ga|determiners|cat2=possessive determiners|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|h}}}}

# [[her]], [[its]]
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' hathair agus '''a''' máthair|her father and mother}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Bhris an mheaig '''a''' heiteog.|The magpie broke its wing.}}

====Determiner====
{{head-lite|ga|determiners|cat2=possessive determiners|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|e}}}}

# [[their]]
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' n-athair agus '''a''' máthair|their father and mother}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' dtithe|their houses}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' n-ainmneacha|their names}}
# {{lb|ga|Connacht}} [[our]]
# {{lb|ga|Connacht}} [[your]] (''plural'')

=====See also=====
{{Irish personal pronouns}}

====Determiner====
{{head-lite|ga|determiners|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|l}}}}

# [[how]] {{q-lite|used with an abstract noun}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|'''A''' ghéire a labhair sí!|How sharply she spoke!}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|'''A''' fheabhas atá sé!|How good it is!}}

===Etymology 2===
{{etymid|ga|direct relative particle}}
A reduced form of older {{m-lite|ga|do}} (itself a reanalysis of {{m-lite|ga|do}} used in past tenses, and also present in early modern verbs like {{m-lite|ga|do-bheirim|t=I give}}, {{m-lite|ga|do-chím|t=I see}}), or from the preverb {{m-lite|ga|a-}} in early modern verbs like {{m-lite|ga|a-tú|t=I am}}, {{m-lite|ga|a-deirim|t=I say}} in relative clauses.

====Particle====
{{head-lite|ga|particles|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|l}} except of {{m-lite|ga|d’}} and of past autonomous forms}}

# {{ng-lite|introduces a direct relative clause, takes the independent form of an irregular verb}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an fear '''a''' chuireann síol|the man who sows seed}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an síol '''a''' chuireann an fear|the seed that the man sows}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an síol '''a''' cuireadh|the seed that was sown}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|nuair '''a''' bhí mé óg|when I was young}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an cat '''a''' d'ól an bainne|the cat that drank the milk}}

====References====
* {{cite-book|author=Gerald O’Nolan|year=1920|volume=1|title=Studies in Modern Irish|pages=89, 93–94|url=https://archive.org/details/studiesinmoderni01onol/page/89/mode/2up}}

===Etymology 3===
{{etymid|ga|indirect relative particle}}
From {{inh-lite|ga|sga|a|a|t=that, which {{ng-lite|the relative particle used after prepositions}}}}, reanalyzed as an independent indirect relative particle from forms like {{m-lite|ga|ar a|t=on which, on whom}}, {{m-lite|ga|dá|t=to which, to whom}}, or early modern {{m-lite|ga|le a|t=with which, with whom}}, {{m-lite|ga|agá|t=at which, at whom}} when prepositional pronouns started to be repeated in such clauses (eg. ''don té agá mbíon cloidheamh (…) aige'', ''daoine agá mbíonn grádh aco do Dhia''). Compare the forms used in Munster instead: {{m-lite|ga|go}} (from {{m-lite|ga|agá|t=at which}}) and {{m-lite|ga|na}} (from {{m-lite|ga|i n-a|t=in which}}, {{m-lite|ga|go n-a|t=with which}}, {{m-lite|ga|ria n-a|t=before which}} and later {{m-lite|ga|lena|t=with which}}, {{m-lite|ga|tréna|t=through which}}).

====Particle====
{{head-lite|ga|particles|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|e}}, takes the dependent form of an irregular verb; not used in the past tense except with some irregular verbs}}

# {{ng-lite|introduces an indirect relative clause}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an bord '''a''' raibh leabhar air|the table on which there was a book}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an fear '''a''' bhfuil a mhac ag imeacht|the man whose son is going away}}

=====Related terms=====
* {{l-lite|ga|ar}} {{q-lite|used with the past tense of regular and some irregular verbs}}

====Pronoun====
{{head-lite|ga|pronouns|cat2=relative pronouns|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|e}}, takes the dependent form of an irregular verb; not used in the past tense except with some irregular verbs}}

# [[all]] [[that]], [[whatever]]
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Sin '''a''' bhfuil ann.|That's all that is there.}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|An bhfuair tú '''a''' raibh uait?|Did you get all that you wanted?}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Íocfaidh mé as '''a''' gceannóidh tú.|I will pay for whatever you buy.}}

=====Related terms=====
* {{l-lite|ga|ar}} {{q-lite|used with the past tense of regular and some irregular verbs}}

====References====
* {{R:ga:SnaG|chapter=5|page=464|text=Tháinig nós chun cinn sa 17ú haois freisin an réamhfhocal a dhúbláil: ''don té agá mbíonn cloidheamh..aige; daoine agá mbíonn grádh aco do Dhia'' (Ó Cuív, 1952b, 177), ''an tí ag a bhfuil a bheag do chuntabhairt aige'' (Williams, 1986, 155).}}
* {{cite-book|title=The New Era Grammar of Modern Irish|author=Gerald O’Nolan|page=56|year=1934|publisher=The Educational Company of Ireland Ltd.}}

===Etymology 4===
{{etymid|ga|vocative particle}}

====Particle====
{{head-lite|ga|particles|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|l}}}}

# {{ng-lite|introduces a vocative}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|'''A''' Dhia!|O God!}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|'''A''' dhuine uasail!|Sir!}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Tar isteach, '''a''' Sheáin.|Come in, Seán.}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|'''A''' amadáin!|You fool!}}

===Etymology 5===
{{etymid|ga|numeral particle}}

====Particle====
{{head-lite|ga|particles|langname=Irish}} {{q-lite|triggers {{ga-mut-link|h}}}}

# {{ng-lite|introduces a numeral}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|'''a''' haon, '''a''' dó, '''a''' trí...|one, two, three...}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|Séamas '''a''' Dó|James the Second}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|bus '''a''' seacht|bus seven}}

===Etymology 6===
{{etymid|ga|preposition}}
Originally a reduced form of {{m-lite|ga|do}}.

====Preposition====
{{head-lite|ga|prepositions|plus dative, triggers [[Appendix:Irish mutations#Lenition|lenition]]|cat2=prepositions governing the dative|langname=Irish}}

# [[to]] {{q-lite|used with verbal nouns}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|síol '''a''' chur|to sow seed}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|uisce '''a''' ól|to drink water}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|ga|an rud atá sé '''a''' scríobh|what he is writing}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|D’éirigh sé '''a''' chaint.|He rose to speak.}}
#: {{ux-lite|ga|Téigh '''a''' chodladh.|Go to sleep.}}

===Mutation===
{{ga-mut}}

