==Italian==

===Etymology 1===
From {{der-lite|it|la|-}} {{m-lite|la|a|ā|pos=''the name of the letter'' {{m-lite|la|A}}}}.

====Pronunciation====
{{it-pr|a*<audio:It-a.ogg>}}

====Letter====
{{it-letter}}

# {{Latn-def-lite|it|letter|1|a|langname=Italian}}

====Noun====
{{head-lite|it|nouns|g=f|cat2=indeclinable nouns|cat3=countable nouns|[[Appendix:Glossary#invariable|invariable]]|langname=Italian}}

# {{Latn-def-lite|it|name|A|a|langname=Italian}}; {{l-lite|en|a}}

=====See also=====
* {{list:Latin script letter names/it/simple}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh-lite|it|la|ad}}. In a few phrases, ''a'' stems from Latin {{m-lite|la|a}}, {{m-lite|la|ab}}.<!--<ref>Angelo Prati, "Vocabolario Etimologico Italiano", Torino, 1951</ref>-->

====Preposition====
{{anchor|italian-preposition}}
{{head-lite|it|prepositions|langname=Italian}}

# {{ng-lite|indicates the [[indirect object]]}}; [[to]]
#: {{ux-lite|it|Porta questo cesto '''a'''lla nonna.|Bring this basket '''to''' grandma.}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|'''A'''i gatti piacciono i pesci.|Cats like fish.|lit=Fish are pleasable '''to''' cats.}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|E lo chiedi '''a''' me?|You're asking that '''to''' me?}}
# {{ng-lite|indicates the place, used in some contexts, in others {{m-lite|it|in}} is used}}; [[in]], [[to]]
#: {{ux-lite|it|Andiamo '''a''' casa?|Can we go home?|lit=Can we go '''to''' home?}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|Ora sto '''a''' Palermo, '''a''' Roma ci torno domani.|I'm '''in''' Palermo now, I'll go back '''to''' Rome tomorrow.}}
# {{ng-lite|denotes the manner}}; [[with]]
#: {{lang-lite|it|''[[appena]], [[a nuoto]], [[a piedi]], [[a caso]]''}}
# {{senseid|it|style}} {{ng-lite|forms adverbs meaning "in a manner related or resembling ~"}}
#: {{lang-lite|it|''[[a cappella]], [[a bestia]], [[a braccio]], [[a pennello]], etc.''}}
# ''This term needs a translation to English. Please help out and '''add a translation'''.'' [[Category:Requests for definitions in Italian entries]]
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|it|'''A''' domani!|[See you] tomorrow!}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|it|'''A''' dopo!|[See you] later!}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|it|'''A'''l prossimo Natale!|[See you] next Christmas!}}
# {{ng-lite|introduces the ingredients of a dish, perfume, etc.}}; [[with]]
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|it|pasta '''a'''ll'uovo|pasta '''with''' eggs}}
#: {{ux-lite|inline=1|it|cornetto '''a'''l cioccolato|chocolate croissant}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|inline=1|shampoo '''a'''l limone|lemon shampoo}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|inline=1|patatine '''a'''lla pizza|pizza'''-flavoured''' crisps}}
# {{lb|it|CS}} {{ng-lite|denotes the direct object, but only if it's not preceded by articles}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|Chiama '''a''' Paolo.|Call Paolo.}}
#: {{ux|it|E non ci avevi visto '''a''' noi?|And you didn't see us?|footer=the "us" here is repeated twice for emphasis}}
#: {{ux-lite|it|Ascolti '''a''' me, signó!|Listen to me, ma'am!}}

=====Usage notes=====
* When followed by a word that begins with a vowel sound, the form {{m-lite|it|ad}} is used instead.
* When followed by the definite article, {{m-self|it|a}} combines with the article to produce the following combined forms:
: {|class="wikitable"
|-
! {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + article
! Combined form
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|il}}
|{{l-lite|it|al}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|lo}}
|{{l-lite|it|allo}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|l'}}
|{{l-lite|it|all'}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|i}}
|{{l-lite|it|ai}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|gli}}
|{{l-lite|it|agli}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|la}}
|{{l-lite|it|alla}}
|-
| {{l-self-lite|it|a}} + {{l-lite|it|le}}
|{{l-lite|it|alle}}
|}

