===Etymology 8===
From {{der-lite|nb|da|ah|t=oh}}, likely from {{der-lite|nb|de|ach|t=oh}}, from {{der-lite|nb|gmh|ach}}, from {{der-lite|nb|goh|ah}}. Also see {{m-lite|nb|ah}} and {{m-lite|nb|akk}}.

====Interjection====
{{head-lite|nb|interjections|langname=Norwegian Bokmål}}

# {{ng-lite|expression of [[surprise]] or [[horror]]}}
#* {{quote-lite|nb|year=1888|author=Herman Colditz|title=Kjærka, et Atélierinteriør|passage=a, det er bare noe drit til han terracottaen|t=oh, that is just some crap for that terracotta guy}}
#: {{ux-lite|nb|a, for noe tøv!|oh, such nonsense!}}
# {{ng-lite|expression of [[admiration]] or [[happiness]]}}
#* {{quote-lite|nb|year=1897|author={{w|Fridtjof Nansen}}|title=Fram over Polhavet I|page=345|passage=a, kunde vi bare gi «Fram» slige vinger|t=oh, if only we could give "Fram" wings like that}}
#: {{ux-lite|nb|a, det gjorde godt!|oh, that felt good!}}
# {{ng-lite|used with the words yes and no to give a sense of [[impatience]] or [[rejection]]}}
#* {{quote-lite|nb|year=1874|author={{w|Henrik Ibsen}}|title=Fru Inger til Østråt|page=99|passage=a nej, det kan være det samme|t=oh no, it does not matter}}
#* {{quote-lite|nb|year=1874-1878|author={{w|Bjørnstjerne Bjørnson}}|title=Brytnings-år I|page=25|passage=a ja, lad Schirmer tegne staburet|t=oh yes, let Schirmer draw the storehouse}}
#* {{quote-lite|nb|year=1988|author={{w|Arild Nyquist}}|title=Giacomettis forunderlige reise|passage=verden er vakker, bestemor. Selv når det regner og blåser. A ja da.|t=the world is beautiful, grandma. Even when it's raining and windy. Oh yes.}}
#: {{ux-lite|nb|a jo, men hold nå fred!|oh yes, but keep quiet now}}

===Etymology 9===
Mostly likely from Norwegian {{m-lite|nb|ad||against, on}}, from {{der-lite|nb|da|ad||by, at}}, from {{der-lite|nb|gmq-oda|at}}, from {{der-lite|nb|non|at||at, to}}, from {{der|nb|gem-pro|*at||at, toward, to}}, from {{der|nb|ine-pro|*h₂éd||to, at}}.

