==Welsh==

===Etymology 1===

====Alternative forms====
* {{q-lite|with [[grave accent]] to indicate otherwise unpredictable short vowel}} {{l-lite|cy|à}}
* {{q-lite|with [[acute accent]] to indicate unusually stressed short vowel}} {{l-lite|cy|á}}
* {{q-lite|with [[circumflex]] to indicate otherwise unpredictable or unusually stressed long vowel}} {{l-lite|cy|â}}
* {{q-lite|with [[diaeresis]] to indicate disyllabicity}} {{l-lite|cy|ä}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA-lite|cy|/aː/}}

====Letter====
{{head-lite|cy|letters|lower case||upper case|A|langname=Welsh}}

# {{Latn-def-lite|cy|letter|1|a|langname=Welsh}} ''It is followed by {{l-lite|cy|b}}.''

=====Mutation=====
* a cannot be mutated but, being a vowel, does take {{l-lite|en|h-prothesis}}, for example with the word {{m-lite|cy|afal||apple}}:
{{cy-mut|afal}}

=====Derived terms=====
* Digraph sequences: {{l-lite|cy|ae}}, {{l-lite|cy|ai}}, {{l-lite|cy|au}}, {{l-lite|cy|aw}}, {{l-lite|cy|ay}}

=====See also=====
* [[Wiktionary:About Welsh#Alphabetization|see other Welsh letters and their names]]

====Noun====
{{cy-noun|f|âu}}

# {{Latn-def-lite|cy|name|A|a|langname=Welsh}}

=====Mutation=====
{{cy-mut}}

===Etymology 2===

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA-lite|cy|/aː/}}

====Verb====
{{head-lite|cy|verb forms|langname=Welsh}}

# {{lb|cy|colloquial}} {{inflection of|cy|mynd||1|s|futr}}

=====Synonyms=====
* {{l-lite|cy|af}} {{q-lite|literary}}

===Etymology 3===
From {{inh-lite|cy|owl|a|a(c)}}, from {{inh|cy|cel-bry-pro|*(h)a}}, from {{inh|cy|ine-pro|*ad-gʰe}} (compare {{cog-lite|cy|ag}} and {{cog-lite|kw|ha}}).

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA-lite|cy|/a/}}

====Conjunction====
{{head-lite|cy|conjunctions|langname=Welsh}} {{q-lite|triggers aspirate mutation (but not always in colloquial language)}}

# [[and]]

=====Synonyms=====
* {{l-lite|cy|ac}} {{q-lite|used before a vowel}}

===Etymology 4===

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA-lite|cy|/aː/|/a/}}

====Pronoun====
{{head-lite|cy|pronouns|langname=Welsh}} {{q-lite|triggers soft mutation}}

# {{lb|cy|relative}} that, which, who ''(used in 'direct' relative clauses, i.e. where the pronoun refers to the subject or the direct object of an inflected verb (as opposed to a periphrastic construction with ''[[bod#Welsh|bod]]'', to be)).''
#: {{ux-lite|cy|Y dyn '''a w'''elais i|inline=1|The man '''that''' I saw}}

=====Usage notes=====
# ''a'' is not used with the third person singular present of the verb bod, where the relative verb form ''[[sydd#Welsh|sydd]]'' is used instead
#: {{ux-lite|cy|Mae'r dyn yn ifanc|inline=1|The man is young}}
#: Not ''*Y dyn '''a''' yw'n ifanc'' but ''Y dyn '''sydd''' yn ifanc''
# ''a'' is not used in indirect relative clauses, where the pronoun is part of a genitive or periphrastic construction. Instead the second relative pronoun ''[[y#Welsh|y]]'' is used
#: {{ux-lite|cy|Oedd chwaer y dyn yma|inline=1|The man's sister was here}}
#: "The man whose sister was here": not ''*Y dyn '''a''' oedd ei chwaer yma'' but ''Y dyn '''yr''' oedd ei chwaer yma''

