===Preposition===
{{en-prep}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Indicating destination:}} In the [[direction]] of, so as to [[arrive]] at.
#: {{ux|en|We are walking '''to''' the shop.}}
#* '''2013''' September 28, [[w:Kenan Malik|Kenan Malik]], "[http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/29/opinion/sunday/london-is-special-but-not-that-special.html?ref=opinion London Is Special, but Not That Special]," ''New York Times'' <small>(retrieved 28 September 2013)</small>:
#*: Driven by a perceived political need to adopt a hard-line stance, Mr. Cameron’s coalition government has imposed myriad new restrictions, the aim of which is to reduce net migration '''to''' Britain to below 100,000.
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate the target or recipient of an action.}}
#: {{ux|en|I gave the book '''to''' him.}}
#: {{ux|en|I spoke '''to''' him earlier.}}
#: {{ux|en|He devoted himself '''to''' education.}}
#: {{ux|en|They drank '''to''' his health.}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate result of action.}}
#: {{ux|en|His face was beaten '''to''' a pulp.}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate a resulting feeling or emotion.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''To''' everyone's great relief, the tuneless carol singers finally ceased their warbling.}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used after an adjective to indicate its application.}}
#: {{ux|en|similar '''to''' ...'', ''relevant '''to''' ...'', ''pertinent '''to''' ...'', ''I was nice '''to''' him'', ''he was cruel '''to''' her'', ''I am used '''to''' walking.}}
# {{n-g|Denotes the end of a range.}}
#: {{ux|en|It takes 2 '''to''' 4 weeks to process typical applications.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|}} [[as|As]] [[a]].
#: ''With God '''to''' friend'' (with God as a friend);&nbsp;&nbsp; ''with The Devil '''to''' fiend'' (with the Devil as a foe);&nbsp;&nbsp; ''lambs slaughtered '''to''' lake'' (lambs slaughtered as a sacrifice);&nbsp;&nbsp; ''took her '''to''' wife'' (took her as a wife);&nbsp;&nbsp; ''was sold '''to''' slave'' (was sold as a slave).
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate a [[ratio]] or [[comparison]];}} [[compare]]d to, [[as against]].
#: ''one '''to''' one'' = 1:1
#: ''ten '''to''' one'' = 10:1.
#: ''I have ten dollars '''to''' your four.''
#* {{RQ:Marlowe Tamburlaine|1|II|iii|page=33|The hoſt of ''Xerxes'', which by fame is ſaid<br>To drinke the mightie Parthian ''Araris'',<br>Was but a handfull '''to''' that we will haue.}}
#* {{quote-journal
|en
|date=April 22, 2012
|author=Sam Sheringham
|title=Liverpool 0-1 West Brom
|work=BBC Sport
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17718147
|page=
|passage=In total, the Reds had 28 shots '''to''' their opponent's nine, and 15 corners to the Baggies' three.}}
# {{lb|en|arithmetic}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the preceding term is to be [[raise]]d to the [[power]] of the following value; indicates [[exponentiation]]}}.
#: ''Three squared or three '''to''' the second power is nine.''
#: ''Three '''to''' the power of two is nine.''
#: ''Three '''to''' the second is nine.''
# {{lb|en|time}} [[preceding|Preceding]] the next hour.
#: ''What's the time? – It's quarter '''to''' four in the afternoon (or 3:45 pm).''
#: {{ant|en|past}}
## {{lb|en|informal}} Often used without the hour
##: ''It’s quarter '''to''' (3:45, or 4:45, or whatever time ending in 45 would make the most sense)''
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to describe what something consists of or contains.}}
#: ''Anyone could do this job; there's nothing '''to''' it.''
#: ''There's a lot of sense '''to''' what he says.''
#: ''The name has a nice ring '''to''' it.''
# [[according to]]
#: ''Our holiday did not go '''to''' plan.''
# {{lb|en|Canada|Newfoundland|West Midlands|_|(UK)}} [[at|At]].
#: ''Stay where you're '''to''' and I'll come find you, b'y.''

====Usage notes====
In the sense of "as a", it is a [[fossil word]] <small>(Standard English only)</small>, found usually only in obsolete set phrases like: "''to take a woman '''to''' wife''", "''to have someone '''to''' friend''", "''to have something '''to''' birthright''" etc. In northern dialects, where it is rare but still in common use, it is often used in combination with {{m|en|with}}.

