==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{q|stressed}}
** {{a|RP|GA|CA|AusE}} {{enPR|ĭn}}, {{IPA-lite|en|/ɪn/}}
** {{a|NZ}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ɘn/}}
** {{audio|en|en-us-in.ogg|Audio (US)}}
** {{audio|en|en-au-in.ogg|Audio (AU)}}
* {{q|unstressed}}
** {{a|RP}} {{enPR|ĭn}}, {{IPA-lite|en|/ɪn/}}
** {{a|GA|CA|AusE}} {{enPR|ən}}, {{IPA-lite|en|/ən/}}
** {{a|NZ}} {{IPA-lite|en|/ɘn/}}
* {{rhymes-lite|en|ɪn|s=1}}
* {{homophones|en|inn}}

===Etymology 1===
{{PIE word|en|h₁en}}
Preposition and verb from {{inh|en|enm|in}}, from {{inh|en|ang|in}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*in}}.{{dercat|en|ine-pro|inh=1}}

Adverb, noun and adjective from {{inh|en|enm|in}}, from {{inh|en|ang|inn}} and {{m|ang|inne}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*innai}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|en|i'||colloquial|poetic}}

====Preposition====
[[File:Le Bounty.jpg|thumb|right|A ship '''in''' a bottle.]]
[[File:Bichon Frisé in sink.jpg|thumb|right|A dog '''in''' a sink.]]
{{en-prep}}

# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate location, inclusion, or position within spatial, temporal or other limits.}}
## [[contain|Contained]] by.
##: {{ux-lite|en|The dog is '''in''' the kennel.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|There were three pickles '''in''' a jar.}}
## [[within|Within]] the bounds or limits of.
##: {{ux-lite|en|I like living '''in''' the city.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|There are lots of trees '''in''' the park.}}
##* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-08-03|volume=408|issue=8847|magazine={{w|The Economist}}| title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21582498-america-has-changed-way-it-measures-gdp-boundary-problems Boundary problems]| passage=GDP measures the total value of output '''in''' an economic territory.}}
## [[surround|Surrounded]] by; [[among]]; [[amidst]].
##: {{ux-lite|en|We are '''in''' the enemy camp.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|Her plane is '''in''' the air.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|Waiter! There's a fly '''in''' my soup!}}
## {{senseid|en|wearing}} Wearing (an item of clothing).
##: ''I glanced over at the pretty girl '''in''' the red dress.''
## [[part|Part]] of; a [[member]] of; out of; from among.
##: {{ux-lite|en|You are one '''in''' a million.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|She's '''in''' an orchestra.}}
## {{senseid|en|during}} [[during|During]] (a period of time).
##: {{ux-lite|en|My birthday is '''in''' the first week of December.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en| Easter falls '''in''' the fourth lunar month.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|The country reached a high level of prosperity '''in''' his first term.}}
## {{senseid|en|within}} [[within|Within]] (a certain elapsed time); by the end of.
##: {{ux-lite|en|Will you be able to finish this '''in''' a week?}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|The massacre resulted in over 1000 deaths '''in''' three hours.}}
## {{senseid|en|at the end}} At the end of (a period of [[time]]).
##: {{ux-lite|en|They said they would call us '''in''' a week.}}
## {{lb|en|grammar|phonetics}} Characterized by.
##: {{ux-lite|en|Many English nouns '''in''' ''-is'' form their plurals '''in''' ''-es''.}}
# [[into|Into]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=January 8, 2011|author=Paul Fletcher|work=BBC| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/fa_cup/9341905.stm Stevenage 3-1 Newcastle]| passage=The ball was accidentally kicked '''in''' Kevin Nolan's face in the opening seconds of the contest – an incident that set the tone for an extremely uncomfortable encounter for the Premier League side.}}
#: {{ux-lite|en|Less water gets '''in''' your boots this way.}}
#: {{ux-lite|en|She stood there looking '''in''' the window longingly.}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate limit, qualification, condition, or circumstance.}}
#* {{RQ:Falkner Moonfleet|chapter=4|passage='''In''' returning to the vault, I had no very sure purpose in mind; only a vague surmise that this finding of Blackbeard's coffin would somehow lead to the finding of his treasure.}}
#: {{ux-lite|en|'''In''' replacing the faucet washers, he felt he was making his contribution to the environment.}}
## {{non-gloss definition|Indicating an order or arrangement.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|My fat rolls around '''in''' folds.}}
## {{senseid|en|state}} {{non-gloss definition|Denoting a [[state]] of the subject.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|He stalked away '''in''' anger.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|John is '''in''' a coma.}}
## {{non-gloss definition|Indicates, connotatively, a place-like form of someone's (or something's) personality, as his, her or its psychic and physical characteristics.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|You've got a friend '''in''' me.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|He's met his match '''in''' her.}}
## {{senseid|en|pertaining}} [[pertaining|Pertaining]] to; [[with regard to]].
##: {{ux-lite|en|There has been no change '''in''' his condition.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|What grade did he get '''in''' English?}}
# {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate means, medium, format, genre, or instrumentality.}}
## {{lb|en|of something offered or given in an exchange}} In the form of, in the denomination of.
##: {{ux-lite|en|Please pay me '''in''' cash — preferably '''in''' tens and twenties.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|The deposit can be '''in''' any legal tender, even '''in''' gold.}}
##: ''Her generosity was rewarded '''in''' the success of its recipients.''
##* '''2014''', Carla Bethmann, ''Clean, Friendly, Profitable?: Tourism'', page 114:
##*: {{...}} tourists sometimes attempt to pay '''in''' euros or British pounds.
## {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate a language, script, tone, etc. of a text, speech, etc.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|Beethoven's "Symphony No. 5" '''in''' C minor is among his most popular.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|His speech was '''in''' French, but was simultaneously translated into eight languages.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|When you write '''in''' cursive, it's illegible.}}
##: {{ux-lite|en|Military letters should be formal '''in''' tone, but not stilted.}}

