====Adjective====
{{en-adj}}

# {{lb|en|not comparable}} Located [[indoors]], especially at home or at one's office or place of work.
#: {{ux|en|Is Mr. Smith '''in'''?}}
# {{lb|en|not comparable}} Located [[inside]] something.
#: ''Little by little I pushed the snake into the basket, until finally all of it was '''in'''.''
# {{lb|en|sports|of the ball or other playing implement}} Falling or remaining within the bounds of the playing area.
#: ''If the tennis ball bounces on the line then it's '''in'''.''
# Inserted or fitted into something.
#: {{ux|en|I've discovered why the TV wasn't working – the plug wasn't '''in'''!}}
# Having been collected or received.
#: ''The replies to the questionnaires are now all '''in'''.''
# In fashion; popular.
#: {{ux|en|Skirts are '''in''' this year.}}
# Incoming.
#: {{ux|en|the '''in''' train}}
# {{lb|en|nautical|of the sails of a vessel}} Furled or stowed.
# Of the tide, at or near its highest level.
#: ''You can't get round the headland when the tide's '''in'''.''
# {{lb|en|legal}} With privilege or possession; used to denote a holding, possession, or [[seisin]]<ref>{{R:Burrell LD}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|'''in''' by descent;&emsp;'''in''' by purchase;&emsp;'''in''' of the seisin of her husband}}
# {{lb|en|cricket}} Currently batting.
# Having [[familiarity]] or [[involvement]] ''with'' somebody.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Joe R. Lansdale|title=Flaming Zeppelins: The Adventures of Ned the Seal|page=123|passage=“{{...}} He {{...}} took a rifle out of the batch and shot at me. I was lucky he was such a crummy shot.”<br>“Why would he do that?”<br>“I think he's '''in''' with them, Doctor.”<br>“Them? You mean Ned and Cody?”<br>“All of them. Hickok, the split tail, the whole lot.”}}
#: ''He is very '''in''' with the Joneses.''
