==Old English==

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|ang|gem-pro|*in}}.{{dercat|ang|ine-pro|inh=1}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{ang-IPA|in}}

====Preposition====
{{ang-prep}} {{tlb|ang|Anglian}}

# [[#English|in]]

=====Usage notes=====
In the West Saxon dialect, this word was replaced by {{m|ang|on}} during the separate prehistory of Old English. However, it was still used as a prefix to form many words such as {{m|ang|ingang||entrance}}, {{m|ang|inġewinn||civil war}}, {{m|ang|inġeþanc||inner thoughts}}, {{m|ang|inlendisċ||native}}, {{m|ang|intinga||cause}}, and {{m|ang|inweorc||indoor work}}, and it was still implied by derived adverbs such as {{m|ang|inne||inside}}, {{m|ang|innan||from the inside}}, and {{m|ang|inn}} (“in,” adverb).

=====Descendants=====
* {{desc|enm|in}}
** {{desc|en|in}}
** {{desc|sco|in}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{inh|ang|gem-pro|*inn}}.

====Adverb====
{{ang-adv}}

# {{alt form|ang|inn}}

