{{also|[[Appendix:Collocations of do, have, make, and take]]|hâve}}
==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{qualifier|stressed}} {{IPA|en|/hæv/}}
* {{qualifier|unstressed}} {{IPA|en|/həv/|/əv/|/ə/}}
* {{sense|have to}} {{a|UK|US}} {{IPA|en|/hæf/}}, {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/hæv/}}
* {{q|obsolete|stressed}} {{IPA|en|/heɪv/}}<ref>{{R:Jespersen MEGoHP|I|4.431|129}}</ref>
* {{audio|en|en-us-have.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-to have.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{audio|en|EN-AU ck1 have.ogg|Audio (AU)}}
* {{rhymes|en|æv|s=1}}

===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*keh₂p-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|haven}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hafian}}, {{m|ang|habban|t=to have}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*habbjan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*habjaną|t=to have}}, durative of {{m|gem-pro|*habjaną|t=to lift, take up}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*kh₂pyéti}}, present tense of {{m|ine-pro|*keh₂p-||to take, seize, catch}}. Cognate with {{cog|stq|hääbe||to have}}, {{cog|fy|hawwe||to have}}, {{cog|nl|hebben||to have}}, {{cog|af|hê||to have}}, {{cog|nds|hebben}}, {{m|nds|hewwen||to have}}, {{cog|de|haben||to have}}, {{cog|da|have||to have}}, {{cog|sv|hava||to have}}, {{cog|nn|ha||to have}}, {{cog|is|hafa||to have}}, {{cog|sq|kap||I grab, catch, grip}}<ref>{{R:sq:Orel|kap|page=169}}</ref><ref>{{R:sq:Demiraj|head=kap}}</ref>, {{cog|la|capiō||take|pos=verb}}, {{cog|ru|хапать||to seize}}. More at [[heave]].

Since there is no common Indo-European root for a transitive possessive verb ''have'' (notice that {{cog|la|habeō}} is not etymologically related to English ''have''), Proto-Indo-European probably lacked the ''have'' structure. Instead, the third person forms of ''[[be]]'' were used, with the possessor in [[dative case]], compare Latin ''mihi est / sunt'', literally ''to me is / are''.<ref>[http://books.google.fi/books?id=XlJrPvrGfO0C&pg=PA22&lpg=PA22&dq=%22mihi+est%22+indo-european&source=bl&ots=nQ3y6cgbSp&sig=vpKTQ-OWYXv7dYG3_8RHn9uKYHY&hl=fi&ei=bC3yTP3PKojOswb6xPnyCg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBkQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22mihi%20est%22%20indo-european&f=false Internal Reconstruction in Indo-European: Methods, Results, and Problems]</ref>

====Alternative forms====
* {{alt|en|haue||alternative typography|obsolete}}
* {{alt|en|hae||Scottish-English}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|has|having|had}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[possess]], [[own]].<ref>{{R:OneLook}}</ref>
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' a house and a car.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[hold]], as something at someone's [[disposal]].
#: {{ux|en|Look what I '''have''' here—a frog I found on the street!}}
#: {{ux|en|Do you '''have''' the key?}} (not necessarily one's own key)
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To include as a part, ingredient, or feature.
#: {{ux|en|The stove '''has''' a handle. The shirt '''has''' sleeves.}}
#: {{ux|en|The words ''cow'' and ''dog'' '''have''' three letters.}}
#: {{ux|en|A government '''has''' three branches: the executive, legislative, and judicial.}}
#: {{ux|en|The movie '''has''' lots of action.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} {{n-g|Used to state the existence or presence of someone in a specified relationship with the subject}}.
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' two sisters.}}
#: {{ux|en|She doesn’t '''have''' any friends.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' a really mean boss.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[consume]] or [[use up]] (a particular [[substance]] or [[resource]], especially [[food]] or [[drink]]).
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' breakfast at six o'clock.}}
#: {{ux|en|You've already '''had''' five drinks!}}
#: {{ux|en|She's '''had''' more than enough time already.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[undertake]] or [[perform]] (an action or activity).
#: {{ux|en|Can I '''have''' a look at that?}}
#: {{ux|en|He's '''having''' a tantrum about it.}}
#: {{ux|en|I’m going to '''have''' a bath now.}}
#: {{ux|en|Let’s '''have''' a game of tiddlywinks.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be [[schedule]]d to [[attend]], [[undertake]] or [[participate]] in.
#: {{ux|en|What class do you '''have''' right now? I '''have''' English.}}
#: {{ux|en|Fred won’t be able to come to the party; he '''has''' a meeting that day.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' a lot of work to do.}}
# To [[experience]], [[go through]], [[undergo]].
#: {{ux|en|We '''had''' a hard year last year, with the locust swarms and all that.}}
#: {{ux|en|He '''had''' surgery on his hip yesterday.}}
#: {{ux|en|I’m '''having''' the time of my life!}}
#: {{ux|en|I hope you '''have''' a wonderful birthday.}}
#: {{ux|en|This year we're '''having''' Christmas with my wife's family in Thunder Bay.}}
# To be [[afflict]]ed with, [[suffer]] from.
#: {{ux|en|He '''had''' a cold last week.}}
# {{lb|en|auxiliary verb, taking a [[past participle]]}} {{n-g|Used in forming the [[w:Perfect aspect|perfect aspect]].}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' already eaten today.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''had''' already eaten.}}
#: {{ux|en|I will '''have''' left by the time you get here.}}
# {{n-g|Used as an interrogative verb before a [[pronoun]] to form a [[tag question]], echoing a previous use of 'have' as an auxiliary verb or, in certain cases, main verb. (For further discussion, see the appendix [[Appendix:English tag questions|English tag questions]].)}}
#: {{ux|en|They haven’t eaten dinner yet, '''have they'''?}}
#: {{ux|en|Your wife hasn’t been reading that nonsense, '''has she'''?}}
#: {{ux|en|He has some money, '''hasn’t he'''?}}
# {{lb|en|auxiliary verb, taking a [[w:Infinitive|to-infinitive]]}} ''See'' '''[[have to]]'''.
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' to go.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[give birth]] to.
#: {{ux|en|The couple always wanted to '''have''' children.}}
#: {{ux|en|My wife is '''having''' the baby right now!}}
#: {{ux|en|My mother '''had''' me when she was 25.}}
# {{lb|en|usually passive}} To [[obtain]].
#: ''The substance you describe can't be '''had''' at any price.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To engage in [[sexual intercourse]] with.
#: {{ux|en|He’s always bragging about how many women he’s '''had'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2008|month=January–February|title=70 Ways to Improve Every Day of the Week|journal={{w|Men's Health}}|volume=23|issue=1|issn=1054-4836|page={{gbooks|6ccDAAAAMBAJ|134|have}}|passage=Tame midweek stress the fun way. '''Have''' each other before dinner to reconnect after a long day.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To accept as a [[romantic]] [[partner]].
#: {{ux|en|Despite my protestations of love, she would not '''have''' me.}}
# {{qualifier|transitive with bare infinitive}} To [[cause]] to, by a [[command]], [[request]] or [[invitation]].
#: {{ux|en|They '''had''' me feed their dog while they were out of town.}}
#: {{ux|en|Her very boyfriend is the person the criminal '''has''' do most of her dirty deeds.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|author=Matt Cyr|title=Something to Teach Me: Journal of an American in the Mountains of Haiti|publisher=Educa Vision, Inc.|isbn=1584321385|page={{gbooks|quEn9UyekEgC|25|had}}
|passage=His English is still in its beginning stages, like my Creole, but he was able to translate some Creole songs that he's written into English—not the best English, but English nonetheless. He '''had''' me correct the translations. That kind of thing is very interesting to me. When I was learning Spanish, I would often take my favorite songs and try to translate them.}}
# {{qualifier|transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement}} To [[cause]] to be.
#: {{ux|en|He '''had''' him arrested for trespassing.}}
#: {{ux|en|The lecture’s ending '''had''' the entire audience in tears.}}
#: {{ux|en|Jim '''has''' his eyes closed.}}
# {{qualifier|transitive with bare infinitive}} To be [[affected]] by an occurrence. (Used in supplying a [[topic]] that is not a verb [[argument]].)
#: {{ux|en|The hospital '''had''' several patients contract pneumonia last week.}}
#: {{ux|en|I’ve '''had''' three people today tell me my hair looks nice.}}
# {{qualifier|transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement}} To [[depict]] as being.
#: {{ux|en|Their stories differed; he said he’d been at work when the incident occurred, but her statement '''had''' him at home that entire evening.}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|date=3 May 2011|title=Corrections and clarifications|journal=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/may/03/corrections-clarifications|passage=Anton Rogan, 8, was one of the runners-up in the Tick Tock Box short story competition, not Anton Rogers as we '''had''' it.}}
# {{lb|en|Britain|slang}} To [[defeat]] in a [[fight]]; [[take]].
#: {{ux|en|I could '''have''' him!}}
# {{lb|en|Britain|slang}} To inflict [[punishment]] or [[retribution]] on.
#: {{ux|en|You broke the window! Teacher’ll '''have''' you for that!}}
# {{lb|en|dated|outside|Ireland}} To be able to [[speak]] (a [[language]]).
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' no German.}}
# To [[feel]] or be (especially [[painfully]]) [[aware]] of.
#: {{ux|en|Dan certainly '''has''' arms today, probably from scraping paint off four columns the day before.}}
# {{lb|en|informal|often passive}} To [[trick]], to [[deceive]].
#: {{ux|en|I bought a laptop online but it never arrived. I think I've been '''had'''!}}
#: {{ux|en|You '''had''' me alright! I never would have thought that was just a joke.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|in the negative|often in continuous tenses}} To [[allow]]; to [[tolerate]].
#: {{ux|en|The child screamed incessantly for his mother to buy him a toy, but she wasn't '''having''' any of it.}}
#: {{ux|en|I asked my dad if I could go to the concert this Thursday, but he wouldn't '''have''' it since it's a school night.}}
#* {{RQ:Woolf Jacob's Room|chapter=II|page=19|passage=“ You're a very naughty boy. If I've told you once, I've told you a thousand times. I won't '''have''' you chasing the geese!”}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|often used in the negative}} To [[believe]], [[buy]], be taken in by.
#: {{ux|en|I made up an excuse as to why I was out so late, but my wife wasn't '''having''' any of it.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[host]] someone; to take in as a [[guest]].
#: {{ux|en|Thank you for '''having''' me!}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To get a [[reading]], [[measurement]], or [[result]] from an [[instrument]] or [[calculation]].
#: {{ux|en|What do you '''have''' for problem two?}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''have''' two contacts on my scope.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|of a jury}} To consider a [[court]] [[proceeding]] that has been completed; to begin [[deliberations]] on a case.
#: {{ux|en|We’ll schedule closing arguments for Thursday, and the jury will '''have''' the case by that afternoon.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|birdwatching}} To make an [[observation]] of (a bird species).
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=2005|author=Sean Dooley|authorlink=Sean Dooley|title=The Big Twitch|publisher=Allen and Unwin|location=Sydney|page=57|passage=For some reason, "I '''had''' a Freckled Duck today" never seems to work as a pick-up line.}}

=====Usage notes=====
In certain dialects, expressions, and literary use, the lexical ''have'' can be used without ''do''-support, meaning the sentence ''Do you have an idea?'' can also be ''Have you an idea?'' This makes ''have'' the only lexical verb in Modern English that can function without it, aside from some [[nonce]] examples with other verbs in set phrases, as in ''[[what say you|What say you?]]'', and aside from the verb {{m|en|be}} where this is considered lexical.

The auxiliary ''have'' which forms the perfect tense never uses ''do''-support, so ''Have you seen it?'' cannot be ''Do you have seen it?''.

