==English==
{{wikipedia|You (disambiguation)|You}}

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|ye||archaic nominative, dialectal plural}}
* {{alter|en|ya|yah|yer|yeh|y'|yo|yu|yuh||informal or eye dialect}}
* {{alter|en|-cha||informal, after ''/t/''}}
* {{alter|en|-ja||informal, after'' /d/''}}
* {{alter|en|u||informal, internet}}
* {{alter|en|yoo||eye dialect}}
* {{alter|en|yew||obsolete or eye dialect}}
* {{alter|en|youe|yow|yowe||obsolete}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|you}}, {{m|enm|yow}}, {{m|enm|ȝow|pos=object case of {{m|enm|ye}}}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ēow|t=you|pos=dative case of {{m|ang|ġē}}}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*iwwiz|t=you|pos=dative case of {{m|gem-pro|*jīz}}}}, Western form of {{m|gem-pro|*izwiz|t=you|pos=dative case of {{m|gem-pro|*jūz}}}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*yūs|t=you|pos=plural}}, {{m|ine-pro|*yū́}}.

Cognate with {{cog|sco|you|t=you}}, {{cog|stq|jou|t=you}}, {{cog|fy|jo|t=you}}, {{cog|nds|jo}}, {{m|nds|joe}} and {{m|nds|oe|t=you}}, {{cog|nl|jou}} and {{m|nl|u|t=you}}, {{cog|gmh|eu}}, {{m|gmh|iu|t=you|pos=object pronoun}}, {{cog|la|vōs|t=you}}, {{cog|ae|𐬬𐬋|t=you}}, {{cog|ask|yë̃́|t=you}}, {{cog|bsh|šó|t=you}}, {{cog|sa|यूयम्|tr=yūyám|t=you}}

See usage notes. {{m|en|ye|Ye}}, {{m|en|you}} and {{m|en|your}} are cognate with {{cog|nl|jij}}/{{m|nl|je}}, {{m|nl|jou}}, {{m|nl|jouw}}; {{cog|nds|ji}}, {{m|nds|jo}}/{{m|nds|ju}}, {{m|nds|jug}} and {{cog|de|ihr}}, {{m|de|euch}} and {{m|de|euer}} respectively. {{m|en|ye|Ye}} is also cognate with archaic {{cog|sv|I}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{qualifier|stressed}}
** {{a|RP}} {{enPR|yo͞o}}, {{audio-IPA|en|En-uk-you.ogg|/juː/}}, {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-you.wav|Audio}}
** {{a|GA}} {{enPR|yo͞o}}, {{audio-IPA|en|En-us-you.ogg|/ju/}}
** {{a|Aus}} {{enPR|yo͞o}}, {{IPA|en|/jʉː/}}
** {{rhymes|en|uː|s=1}}
* {{qualifier|unstressed}}
** {{a|RP}} {{enPR|yo͞o}}, {{IPA|en|/ju/}}
** {{a|GA|Aus}} {{enPR|yə}}, {{audio-IPA|en|en-us-you unstressed.ogg|/jə/}}
* {{homophones|en|ewe|u|yew|yu|hew}} {{qualifier|in h-dropping dialects}}, [[hue]] {{qualifier|in h-dropping dialects}}

When a word ending in {{IPAchar|/t/}}, {{IPAchar|/d/}}, {{IPAchar|/s/}}, or {{IPAchar|/z/}} is followed by {{m|en|you}}, these may coalesce with the {{IPAchar|/j/}}, resulting in {{IPAchar|/tʃ/}}, {{IPAchar|/dʒ/}}, {{IPAchar|/ʃ/}} and {{IPAchar|/ʒ/}}, respectively. This is occasionally represented in writing, e.g. {{m|en|gotcha}} (from {{m|en|got}} {{m|en|you}}) or ''[[whatcha]] [[doin']]?'' (more formally ''[[what]] [[are]] [[you]] [[doing]]?'').

