{{also|Let|leť|Leț|lét|lèt|lët|lêt|lết|łęt|Łęt|лет|-let}}
==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|lett}} ''(archaic)''
* {{l|en|lettest}} ''(2nd person singular simple present and simple past; archaic)''
* {{l|en|letteth}} ''(3rd person singular simple present; archaic)''

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/lɛt/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-let.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛt|s=1}}
* {{homophones|en|Lett}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{der|en|enm|leten}}, {{m|enm|læten}}, from {{der|en|ang|sc=Latinx|lǣtan||to allow, let go, bequeath, leave, rent}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*lātan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*lētaną||to leave behind, allow}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*leh₁d-||to let, leave behind}}.

{{rel-top|Cognates}}
Cognate with {{cog|sco|lat}}, {{m|sco|lete||to let, leave}}, {{cog|frr|lete||to let}}, {{cog|fy|litte||to let}}, {{cog|nl|laten||to let, leave}}, {{cog|de|lassen||to let, leave, allow}}, {{cog|sv|låta||to let, allow, leave}}, {{cog|is|láta||to let}}, {{cog|sq|lë||to allow, let, leave}} and partially related to [[French]] {{m|fr|laisser||to let}}. {{rel-bottom}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|lets|letting|let|past2=leet|past2_qual=obsolete|past_ptc2=letten|past_ptc2_qual=obsolete}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[allow]] to, not to prevent {{qualifier|+ infinitive, but usually without {{m|en|to}}}}.
#: {{ux|en|After he knocked for hours, I decided to '''let''' him come in.}}
#* {{RQ:KJV|Exodus|8|28}}
#*: Pharaoh said, I will '''let''' you go.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|act=IV|scene=vi|passage=If your name be Horatio, as I am '''let''' to know it is{{...}}}}
#* '''1971''', {{w|Ursula K. Le Guin}}, ''{{w|The Tombs of Atuan}}''
#*: He could not be '''let'''<!--sic--> die of thirst there alone in the dark.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-21|author={{w|Oliver Burkeman}}| volume=189| issue=2| page=27| magazine={{w|The Guardian Weekly}}| title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/may/10/conscious-computing-twitter-facebook-google The tao of tech]| passage=The dirty secret of the internet is that all this distraction and interruption is immensely profitable. Web companies like to boast about [&hellip;], or offering services that '''let''' you "stay up to date with what your friends are doing",{{...}}and so on. But the real way to build a successful online business is to be better than your rivals at undermining people's control of their own attention.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow to be or do without interference; to not disturb or meddle with; to [[leave]] (someone or something) alone. 
#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me be!}}
#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|book=II|canto=VI|stanza=16|passage=Yet neither spinnes nor cardes, ne cares nor frets, / But to her mother Nature all her care she '''lets'''.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow the release of (a fluid).
#: {{ux|en|The physicians '''let''' about a pint of his blood, but to no avail.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow possession of (a property etc.) in exchange for [[rent]].
#: {{ux|en|I decided to '''let''' the farmhouse to a couple while I was working abroad.}}
#*{{quote-song|en|text=Trailers for sale or rent, rooms to '''let''', fifty cents.|year=1965|author=Roger Miller|title=King Of The Road}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give, grant, or assign, as a work, privilege, or contract; often with ''out''.
#: {{ux|en|to '''let''' the building of a bridge; &emsp;to '''let''' out the lathing and the plastering}}
# {{lb|en|auxiliary|transitive}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to introduce a first or third person imperative verb construction.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Let''''s put on a show!}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' us have a moment of silence.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me just give you the phone number.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' ''P'' be the point where ''AB'' and ''OX'' intersect.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete|_|except with [[know]]}} To [[cause]] {{qualifier|+ bare infinitive}}.
#: {{ux|en|Can you '''let''' me know what time you'll be arriving?}}
#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtDrthr|6.4|2|IV|iv|passage=Soo within a whyle kynge Pellinore cam with a grete hoost / and salewed the peple and the kyng / and ther was grete ioye made on euery syde / Thenne the kyng '''lete''' serche how moche people of his party ther was slayne / And ther were founde but lytel past two honderd men slayne and viij knyȝtes of the table round in their pauelions}}
<!--Prior quote:Thenne the kyng '''lete''' serche how moche people of his party ther was slayne.-->
#* '''1818''', {{w|John Keats}}, "To—":
#*: Time's sea hath been five years at its slow ebb, / Long hours have to and fro '''let''' creep the sand{{nb...}}.

=====Usage notes=====
* The use of “let” to introduce an imperative may sometimes be confused with its use, ''as its own imperative'', in the sense of “to allow”. For example, the sentence “'''Let''' me go to the store.” could either be a second-person imperative of “let” (addressing someone who might prevent the speaker from going to the store) or a first-person singular imperative of “go” (not implying any such preventer).

=====Synonyms=====
* {{sense|to allow}} {{l|en|allow}}, {{l|en|permit}}

