====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# The allowing of possession of a property etc. in exchange for [[rent]].
#*{{quote-book|en|author=Charles Dickens|year=1854|text=Then he says “You would call it a Good '''Let''', Madam?”<br>“O certainly a Good Let sir.”|page=317|title=Christmas Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g5IPAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA317&lpg=PA317&dq=You+would+call+it+a+Good+Let,+Madam?%E2%80%9D&source=bl&ots=9BRzev-gor&sig=ACfU3U0YQUKYQyiIkPQgMUw4tCOygSrkUQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNtralhq3pAhUKknIEHUC3CjsQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=You%20would%20call%20it%20a%20Good%20Let%2C%20Madam%3F%E2%80%9D&f=false}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{der|en|enm|letten||to hinder, delay}}, from {{der|en|ang|lettan||to hinder, delay”; literally, “to make late}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*lattjan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*latjaną}}. Akin to {{cog|ang|latian||to delay}}, {{cog|nl|letten}}, {{cog|ang|læt||late}}. More at [[late]], [[delay]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb||||let}}

# {{lb|en|archaic}} To [[hinder]], [[prevent]], [[impede]], [[hamper]], [[cumber]]; to [[obstruct]] (someone or something).
#* {{RQ:King James Version|2 Thessalonians|2|7|passage=He who now '''letteth''' will '''let''', until he be taken out of the way.}}
#* {{RQ:Tennyson Idylls|page=152|passage=Sir King, mine ancient wound is hardly whole, / And '''lets''' me from the saddle; {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[prevent]] someone from doing something; also to [[prevent]] something from happening.
#* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|Acts|8|passage=And as they went on their waye, they cam unto a certayne water, and the gelded man sayde: Se here is water, what shall '''lett''' me to be baptised?}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[tarry]] or [[delay]].
#* {{RQ:Chaucer Canterbury Tales|Shipman's Tale|passage=No longer wold he '''lette'''.|brackets=on}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1826|section=The History of Sir Eger, Sir Grahame, And Sir Gray-Steel|title=Early Metrical Tales; Including the History of Sir Egeir, Sir Gryme, and Sir Gray-Steill|location=Edinburgh|page=7|passage=And for that strake I would not '''let''', / Another upon him soon I set, {{...}}}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[obstacle]] or [[hindrance]].
#* {{RQ:Latimer Sermons|volume=II|sermon=XXV|chapter=Preached on the Twenty First Sunday after Trinity|date=12 June 1552|page=541|passage=[E]ver conſider vvhether our doings be to the '''let''' of our ſalvation or not.}}
#* {{RQ:Ovid Golding Metamorphosis|book=3|lines=60–61|passage=And Cadmus saw his campanie make tarience in that sort / He marveld what should be their '''let''', and went to seeke them out.}}
#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=16|book=II|passage=''Paulus Emilius'' going to the glorious expedition of ''Macedon'', advertised the people of ''Rome'' during his absence not to speake of his actions: ''For the licence of judgements is an especiall '''let''' in great affaires.''}}
# {{lb|en|tennis}} The [[hindrance]] caused by the [[net]] during [[serve]], only if the ball falls legally.

