===Etymology 2===
{{etymid|en|mate}}
From {{der|en|enm|make|id=equal}}, {{m|enm|imake}}, from {{der|en|ang|ġemaca||a mate, an equal, companion, peer}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*gamakô||companion, comrade}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*maǵ-||to knead, oil}}. Reinforced by {{cog|non|maki||an equal}}. Cognate with {{cog|is|maki||spouse}}, {{cog|sv|make||spouse, husband}}, {{cog|da|mage||companion, fellow, mate}}. See also ''[[match]]''.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|UK|dialectal}} [[mate|Mate]]; a spouse or companion; a [[match]].
#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|I|vii|passage=Th'Elfe therewith astownd, / Vpstarted lightly from his looser '''make''', / And his vnready weapons gan in hand to take.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1624|[[w:Ben Jonson|Ben Jonson]]|The Masque of Owls at Kenilworth
|passage=Where their maids and their '''makes''' / At dancing and wakes, / Had their napkins and posies / And the wipers for their noses}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1684|author=Meriton|title=Praise Ale|passage=But then sometimes I thought, it's a black Crake / That never to her-sell can get a '''Make'''.}}
#* '''1678''' (later reprinted: '''1855'''), John Ray, ''A Hand-book of Proverbs'':
#*: Every cake hath its '''make'''; but a scrape cake hath two.

===Etymology 3===
{{unc|en}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{alter|en|meck||Scotland}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|Scotland|Ireland|Northern England|now|rare}} A [[halfpenny]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1826|[[w:Sir Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]]|Woodstock; Or, the Cavalier
|passage=the last we shall have, I take it; for a '''make''' to a million, but we trine to the nubbing cheat to-morrow.}}
#* '''1934''', {{w|Lewis Grassic Gibbon}}, ''Grey Granite'', Polygon 2006 {{qualifier|A Scots Quair}}, page 606:
#*: Only as he climbed the steps did he mind that he hadn't even a '''meck''' upon him, and turned to jump off as the tram with a showd swung grinding down to the Harbour {{...}}

===Etymology 4===
Origin unclear.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|East Anglia|Essex|obsolete}} An agricultural tool resembling a [[scythe]], used to cut (harvest) certain plants such as peas, reeds, or tares.
#* '''1797''', Arthur Young, ''General View of the Agriculture of the County of Suffolk: Drawn Up for the Consideration of the Board of Agriculture and Internal Improvement'', page 73:
#*: ''Harvest.''—When left for seed, they are cut and wadded as pease, with a '''''make'''''.
#*: ''Produce.''—From three to six sacks an acre.
#* '''1811''', William Gooch, ''General view of the agriculture of the county of Cambridge; drawn up for the consideration of the Board of Agriculture and Internal Improvement'', page 142, section VI "Pease":
#*: Harvest. Taken up by a pease-'''make''', and left in small heaps, and turned as often as the weather may make it necessary.

