|page=6|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/cu31924021760941/page/n17/mode/1up|passage=Then there came a reg'lar terror of a sou'wester same as you don't get one summer in a thousand, and blowed the shanty flat and ripped about half of the weir poles out of the sand. We spent consider'ble money '''getting''' 'em reset, and then a swordfish got into the pound and tore the nets all to slathers, right in the middle of the squiteague season.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cause]] to do.
#: {{ux|en|Somehow she '''got''' him to agree to it.}}
#: {{ux|en|I can't '''get''' it to work.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Twelfth Night|act=III|scene=iii|page=268|passage='''Get''' him to say his prayers.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1927| author=[http://openlibrary.org/authors/OL2416183A F. E. Penny]| chapter=5| title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL16814587W Pulling the Strings]| passage=Anstruther laughed good-naturedly. “[&hellip;] I shall take out half a dozen intelligent maistries from our Press and '''get''' them to give our villagers instruction when they begin work and when they are in the fields.”}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to come or go or move.
#: {{ux|en|I '''got''' him to his room.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1881|author=Dante Gabriel Rossetti|authorlink=Dante Gabriel Rossetti|title=Ballads and Sonnets|chapter=Retro me, Sathana !|oclc=946729536|page=252|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=_VsJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA252|text='''Get''' thee behind me.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|with various prepositions, such as [[into]], [[over]], or [[behind]]; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries [[get into]], [[get over]], etc.}} To [[adopt]], [[assume]], [[arrive]] at, or [[progress]] towards (a certain position, location, state).
