==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|frm|idiome}}, and its source, {{der|en|LL.|-}} {{m|la|idioma}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἰδίωμα||a peculiarity, property, a peculiar phraseology, idiom}}, from {{m|grc|ἰδιοῦσθαι||to make one's own, appropriate to oneself}}, from {{m|grc|ἴδιος||one's own, pertaining to oneself, private, personal, peculiar, separate}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈɪdi.əm/}}
* {{audio|en|en-uk-idiom.ogg|Audio (GB)}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-idiom.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɪdi.əm|s=3}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|idiomata}} {{q|sometimes used uncountably}}
{{wikipedia|idiom (language structure)|mul=variety (linguistics)}}

# {{senseid|en|language structure}} A [[manner]] of speaking, a mode of expression peculiar to a [[language]], [[language family]], or group of people<!--"person" is omitted here because [[idiolect]]ic nature is almost never what [[idiomaticness]] has reference to-->.
#: {{ux|en|In English, '''idiom''' requires the indefinite article in a phrase such as "she's an engineer", whereas in Spanish, idiom forbids it.}}
#: {{ux|en|Some of the usage prescriptions improved clarity and were kept; others that yielded discordant violations of '''idiom''' were eventually revised.}}
#: {{synonyms|en|idiomaticness|idiomaticity}}
## {{senseid|en|in programming}} {{lb|en|programming}} A programming construct or phraseology that is characteristic of the language.
##* {{quote-book|en|2005|Magnus Lie Hetland|Beginning Python: From Novice to Professional|page=100|isbn=159059519X
|passage=I have to use the same assignment and call to {{monospace|raw_input}} in two places. How can I avoid that? I can use the {{monospace|while True/break}} '''idiom''': {{...}}}}
# {{senseid|en|language variety}} A [[language]] or [[language]] [[variety]]; specifically, a restricted dialect used in a given historical period, context etc.
#: {{ux|en|In the '''idiom''' of the day, they were sutlers, although today they'd probably be called vendors.}}
#* '''2010''', {{w|Christopher Hitchens}}, "The ''Other'' L-Word", ''Vanity Fair'', 13 Jan 2010:
#*: Many parents and teachers have become irritated to the point of distraction at the way the weed-style growth of "like" has spread through the '''idiom''' of the young.
# {{senseid|en|phrasal expression}} An established phrasal expression whose meaning may not be deducible from the literal meanings of its component words.
#: {{ux|en|She often spoke in '''idioms''', pining for salad days and complaining about pots calling the kettle black.}}
#* '''2008''', Patricia Hampl, “You’re History”, in Patricia Hampl and Elaine Tyler May (editors), ''Tell Me True: Memoir, History, and Writing a Life'', Minnesota Historical Society, {{ISBN|9780873516303}}, [http://books.google.com/books?id=ETz9LJZ5s64C&pg=PA134&dq=idiom page 134]:
#*: ''You’re history'', we say {{...}}. Surely it is an American '''idiom'''. Impossible to imagine a postwar European saying, “You’re history. . . . That’s history,” meaning fuhgeddaboudit, pal.
# {{senseid|en|artistic}} An artistic [[style]] (for example, in art, architecture, or music); an [[instance]] of such a style.
#: {{ux|en|the '''idiom''' of the expressionists}}

