==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰuH-|*h₁es-|*h₂wes-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|been||to be}}. The various forms have three separate origins, which were mixed together at various times in the history of English.
* The forms beginning with ''b-'' come from {{inh|en|ang|bēon||to be, become}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*beuną||to be, exist, come to be, become}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*bʰúHt||to grow, become, come into being, appear}}, from the root {{m|ine-pro|*bʰuH-}}. In particular:<!--moved from [[been]]-->
** Now-dialectal use of ''been'' as an infinitive of ''be'' is either from {{inh|en|enm|been|t=to be}} or an extension of the past participle.
** Now-obsolete use of ''been'' as a plural present tense (meaning "are") is from {{inh|en|enm|been}}, {{m|enm|be}} (present plural of {{m|enm|been|t=to be}}, with the ''-n'' leveled in from the past and subjunctive; compare competing forms {{m|enm|aren}}/{{m|enm|are}}).
** Use of ''been'' as a past participle is from {{inh|en|enm|been|}}, {{m|enm|ybeen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġebēon}}.
* The forms beginning with ''w-'' come from the aforementioned {{inh|en|ang|bēon}}, which shared its past tense with the verb {{m|ang|wesan}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*wesan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wesaną}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂wes-||to reside}}.
* The remaining forms are also from {{inh|en|ang|wesan||to be}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*wesan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*wesaną}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₁ésti}}, from the root {{m|ine-pro|*h₁es-}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/biː/}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-to be.ogg|Audio (RP; “to be”)}}
* {{a|GA}} {{IPA|en|/bi/}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-be.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
* {{rhymes|en|iː|s=1}}
* {{homophones|en|b|bee|Bea}}

====Verb====
{{head|en|verb|[[#Conjugation|highly irregular; see conjugation table]]}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|now|usually|literary}} To [[exist]]; to have real existence, to be alive.
#: {{ux|en|The Universe has no explanation: it just '''is'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Tyndale NT|Matthew|2|18|iij|Rachel wepynge ffor her chyldren&nbsp;/ and wolde nott be comforted becauſe they '''were''' not.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|III|iii|page=265|passage=To '''be''', or not to '''be''': that is the question: / Whether 'tis nobler in the mind to suffer / The slings and arrows of outrageous fortune, / Or to take arms against a sea of troubles, / And by opposing end them?}}
#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=12|book=II|page=351|passage={{...}}it were great sottishnesse, and apparent false-hood, to say, that that '''is''' which is not yet in being, or that already hath ceased from being.}}
#* '''1643''', {{w|Thomas Browne}}, ''Religio Medici'', II.2, [https://books.google.com/books?id=bHljAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA163 link]:
#*: There is surely a peece of Divinity in us, something that '''was''' before the Elements, and owes no homage unto the Sun.
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|author=Andrew Martin Fairbairn|journal=Christ in the Centuries, and Other Sermons|publisher=E.P. Dutton & Company|year=1893|volume=12|page=116|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ArIzAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA116|edition=second|passage=And after this death there is to be no resurrection. The old man of sin has ceased to '''be'''; once crucified, he lives no more. The death is utter; the end complete.}}
#* {{quote-av|title=[[w:Monty Python's Flying Circus|Monty Python's Flying Circus]]
|episode=Full Frontal Nudity, [[w:Dead Parrot sketch|Dead Parrot sketch]]|author=[[w:Monty Python|Monty Python]]|date=1969-12-07|role=[[w:Mr Praline|Mr Praline]]|actor=[[w:John Cleese|John Cleese]]|1=en|passage=This parrot is no more! It has ceased to '''be'''! It's expired and gone to meet its maker! This is a late parrot! It's a stiff! Bereft of life, it rests in peace! If you hadn't nailed it to the perch it would be pushing up the daisies!}}
#* '''2004''', Richard Schickel, "Not Just an African Story", ''Time'', 13 December:
#*: The genial hotel manager of the past '''is''' no more. Now owner of a trucking concern and living in Belgium, Rusesabagina says the horrors he witnessed in Rwanda "made me a different man."
# {{lb|en|with {{m|en|there}}, or dialectally {{m|en|it}}, as {{glossary|dummy pronoun|dummy subject}}}} To [[exist]].
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|IV|i|page=178|passage=Some men there '''are''' loue not a gaping Pigge: / Some that are mad, if they behold a Cat: / And others, when the bag-pipe sings i’th nose, / Cannot containe their Vrine for affection.}}
#* {{RQ:Austen Persuasion|volume=IV|page=170|passage="There '''is''' a sort of domestic enjoyment to be known even in a crowd, and this you had."}}
#* '''2011''', Mark Sweney, ''The Guardian'', 6 July:
#*: "There has '''been''' lots of commentary on who is staying and who is staying out and this weekend will be the real test," said one senior media buying agency executive who has pulled the advertising for one major client.
#: {{ux|en|There '''is''' just one woman in town who can help us.}}
#: {{ux|en|{{lb|en|or, dialectally:}} It '''is''' just one woman in town who can help us.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[occupy]] a [[place]].
#: {{ux|en|The cup '''is''' on the table.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[occur]], to take place.
#: {{ux|en|When will the meeting '''be'''?}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|in perfect tenses}} {{non-gloss definition|[[elliptical|Elliptical]] form of "be here", "go to and return from" or similar, also extending to certain other senses of "go".}}
#: {{ux|en|The postman has '''been''' today, but my tickets have still not yet come.}}
#: {{ux|en|I have '''been''' to Spain many times.}}
#: {{ux|en|We've '''been''' about twenty miles.}}
#: {{ux|en|I have terrible constipation – I haven't '''been''' for several days.}}
#: {{ux|en|They have '''been''' through a great deal of trouble.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the subject and object are the same.}}
#: {{ux|en|Knowledge '''is''' bliss.}}
#: {{ux|en|Hi, I'''’m''' Jim.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative|mathematics}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the values on either side of an equation are the same.}}
#: {{ux|en|3 times 5 '''is''' fifteen.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the subject is an instance of the predicate nominal.}}
#: {{ux|en|A dog '''is''' an animal.}}
#: {{ux|en|Dogs '''are''' animals.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the subject plays the role of the predicate nominal.}}
#: {{ux|en|François Mitterrand '''was''' president of France from 1981 to 1995.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the subject has the qualities described by an adjective.}}
#: {{ux|en|The sky '''is''' blue.}}
#: {{ux|en|Father, if thou '''be''' willing, remove this cup from me: nevertheless not my will, but thine, be done. (Luke 22:42)}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate that the subject has the qualities described by a noun or noun phrase.}}
#: {{ux|en|The sky '''is''' a deep blue today.}}
# {{lb|en|auxiliary}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the [[passive voice]].}}
#: {{ux|en|The dog '''was''' saved by the boy.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1995|author=C. K. Ogden|title=Psyche: An Annual General and Linguistic Psychology 1920-1952|pageurl=http://books.google.com.br/books?id=43QCzKUXkBYC&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9780415127790|page=13|publisher=C. K. Ogden|passage=Study courses of Esperanto and Ido have '''been''' broadcast.}}
# {{lb|en|auxiliary}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the [[continuous aspect]].}}
#: {{ux|en|The woman '''is''' walking.}}
#: {{ux|en|I shall '''be''' writing to you soon.}}
#: {{ux|en|We liked to chat while we '''were''' eating.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1995|author=C. K. Ogden|title=Psyche: An Annual General and Linguistic Psychology 1920-1952|pageurl=http://books.google.com.br/books?id=43QCzKUXkBYC&pg=PA13#v=onepage&q&f=false|isbn=9780415127790|page=13|publisher=C. K. Ogden|passage=In the possibility of radio uses of a constructed language — and such experiments '''are''' proving successful&mdash;vast sums of money and untold social forces may be involved.}}
# {{lb|en||auxiliary}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to form the perfect aspect with certain intransitive verbs; this was more common in archaic use, especially with verbs indicating motion. "He is ''[[finish]]ed''", and "He is ''[[go]]ne''" are common, but "He is ''[[come]]''" is archaic.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|I|iv|page=133|passage=''They '''are''' not yet come back.''|footer=instead of the modern ''They '''have''' not yet come back.''}}
#* '''1850''', {{w|Dante Gabriel Rossetti}}, ''The Blessed Damozel'', ll.67-68
#*: ‘I wish that he '''were''' come to me, / For he will come,’ she said.
#* Matthew 28:6 (various translations, from the King James Version of '''1611''' to Revised Version of '''1881'''):
#*: He is not here; for he '''is''' risen{{nb...}}.
#* '''1922''', {{w|A. E. Housman}}, {{w|Last Poems}} XXV, l.13, [https://archive.org/details/lastpoems00hous/page/51/mode/1up page 51]:
#*: ''The King with half the East at heel '''is''' marched from lands of morning;''
# {{lb|en|formal|auxiliary}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to express future action as well as what is due to, intended to, or should happen<!--The fifth example "I am to leave" is indicative, not subjunctive. The sixth is subjunctive, but only incidentally. They are both future periphrastic.-->.}}
#: {{ux|en|They '''are''' to be married next month.}}
#: {{ux|en|They '''are''' to stay here until I return.}}
#: {{ux|en|They '''are''' not to be blamed.}}
#: {{ux|en|How '''are''' they to get out of this mess?}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''am''' to leave tomorrow.}}
#: {{ux|en|I would drive you, '''were''' I to obtain a car.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to link a subject to a [[measurement]].}}
#: {{ux|en|This building '''is''' three hundred years old.}}
#: {{ux|en|I '''am''' 75 kilograms.}}
#: {{ux|en|He'''’s''' about 6 feet tall.}}
# {{lb|en|copulative|with a cardinal numeral}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to state the [[age]] of a subject in years.}}
#: {{ux|en|I'''’m''' 20 (years old).}}
# {{lb|en|with a {{glossary|dummy pronoun|dummy subject}} {{m|en|it}}}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate the time of day.}}
#: {{ux|en|It '''is''' almost eight (o’clock).}}
#: {{ux|en|It'''’s''' 8:30'' [read ''eight-thirty''] ''in Tokyo.}}
#: {{ux|en|What time is it there? It’s night.}}
# {{lb|en|With {{m|en|since}}}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate passage of [[time]] since the occurrence of an [[event]].}}
#: {{ux|en|It has '''been''' three years since my grandmother died. (similar to "My grandmother died three years ago", but emphasizes the intervening period)}}
#: {{ux|en|It had '''been''' six days since his departure, when I received a letter from him.}}
# {{lb|en|rare|and|regional|chiefly|in the past tense}} {{n-g|Used to link two noun clauses, the first of which is a day of the week, recurring date, month, or other specific time (on which the event of the [[main clause]] took place), and the second of which is a period of time indicating how long ago that day was.}} {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|I saw her Monday '''was''' a week: I saw her a week ago last Monday (a week before last Monday).}}
#: {{ux|en|On the morning of Sunday '''was''' fortnight before Christmas: on the morning of the Sunday that was two weeks before the Sunday prior to Christmas.}}
#* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|volume=V|page=97|passage=Miss Lardner (whom you have seen at her cousin Biddulph's) saw you at St James's church on Sunday '''was''' fortnight.}}
#* '''1770''', Ireland, ''Historical Memoirs of the Irish Rebellion, in the year 1641 ... In a letter to Walter Harris, Esq; [By John Curry.] The fourth edition, with corrections throughout the whole, and large additions, by the author'', page 186:
#*: And so, without as much as to return home to furnish myself for such a journey, volens, nolens, they prevailed, or rather forced me to come to Dublin to confer with those colonels, and that was the last August '''was''' twelvemonth.
#* '''1803''', Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons, ''Journals of the House of Commons'', page 249:
#*: That they were present at the Election in August '''was''' Twelvemonth, at which there was the strictest Scrutiny that ever they saw in their Lives, by all the Four Candidates.
#* {{RQ:Scott Guy Mannering|volume=I|chapter=V|pages=79-80|pageref=79|passage=Allow me to recommend some of the kipper—It was John Hay that catched it Saturday '''was''' three weeks.}}
#* {{RQ:Eliot Adam Bede|volume=III|page=53|passage=“Did there come no young woman here—very young and pretty—Friday '''was''' a fortnight, to see Dinah Morris?”}}
#* '''1895''', Miss M. E. Rope of Suffolk, quoted by Joseph Wright, in ''The English Dialect Dictionary'', page 202:
#*: 'Twas there to-morrow '''is''' a week.
#* '''1907''', {{w|John Millington Synge}}, ''The Playboy of the Western World'', I, [https://archive.org/details/playboyofwestern0000syng_q6r6/page/20/mode/1up page 20]:
#*: I killed my poor father, Tuesday '''was''' a week, for doing the like of that.
#* '''1920''' (published), St. George Kieran Hyland, ''A Century of Persecution Under Tudor and Stuart Sovereigns from Contemporary Records'', London, Paul, page 402, quoting an earlier document, ''Loosley'' volume 5, no. 28, "List of Prisoners: In Sir W. More's handwriting": :
#*: Theobald Green gent dead in the Marshalsea in August '''was''' twelvemonth
#*: John Grey gent delivered out of the Marshalsea about August last by Mr. Secretary and remains in St. Mary Overies.
#*: John Jacob gent delivered out of the Marsh. the XVII of May '''was''' twelvemonth and sent to Bridewell by order of the Council.
# {{lb|en|often|impersonal|with {{m|en|it}} as a {{glossary|dummy pronoun|dummy subject}}}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to indicate [[weather]], [[air]] [[quality]], or the like.}}
#: {{ux|en|It '''is''' hot in Arizona, but it '''is''' not usually humid.}}
#: {{ux|en|Why '''is''' it so dark in here?}}
# {{lb|en|[[be#English-dynamic_conjugation|dynamic / lexical "be"]]|especially in progressive tenses|conjugated non-suppletively in the present tense|see usage notes}} To exist or behave in a certain way.
#* '''2006''' October 9, Kristin Newman (writer), Barney Stinson (character), ''[[w:How I Met Your Mother|How I Met Your Mother]]'', season 2, episode 1:
#*: "When I get sad, I stop being sad and '''be''' awesome instead."
#: {{ux|en|"What do we do?" "We '''be''' ourselves."}}
#:{{ux|en|When I play fantasy games, I always '''be''' a gnome.}}
#: {{ux|en|Why is he '''being''' nice to me?}}
# {{lb|en|AAVE|Caribbean|auxiliary|not conjugated}} To tend to do, often do; {{non-gloss definition|marks the [[w:Habitual be|habitual aspect]].}}
#* '''1996''', David Sheffield, Barry W. Blaustein, Tom Shadyac and Steve Oedekerk, screenplay of ''The Nutty Professor''
#*: Women '''be''' shoppin’! You cannot stop a woman from shoppin’!
#* '''2020''', {{w|Moneybagg Yo}}, ''Thug Cry''
#*: Niggas '''be''' tellin' these bitches 'bout business

=====Usage notes=====
* When used copulatively with a pronoun, traditional grammar puts the pronoun in the [[subjective case]] ({{m|en||I}}, {{m|en||he}}, {{m|en||she}}, {{m|en||we}}, {{m|en||they}}) rather than the [[objective case]] ({{m|en||me}}, {{m|en||him}}, {{m|en||her}}, {{m|en||us}}, {{m|en||them}}), regardless of which side of the copula it is placed. For example, “''I was the masked man''” and “''The masked man was I''” would both be considered correct, while “''The masked man was me''” and “''Me was the masked man''” would both be incorrect. However, most colloquial speech treats the verb ''be'' as transitive, in which case the pronoun is used in the objective case if it occurs after the copula: “''I was the masked man''” but “''The masked man was me''”. This paradigm applies even if the copula is linking two pronouns; thus “''I am her''” and “''She is me''", and “''Am I me?''” (versus the traditional “''I am she''”, “''She is I''”, “''Am I I?''”). However, the use of ''whom'' with a copula is generally considered incorrect and a [[hypercorrection]], though in some cases (especially in sentences involving a [[to-infinitive]] or a perfect tense), such as “''Whom do you want to be?''”, it can come naturally to some speakers; in short, straightforward sentences, such as “''Whom are you?''”, this is much rarer and likelier to be considered incorrect.
* Except senses 12 (auxiliary forming the passive voice), 13 (auxiliary forming the continuous aspect) and 22 (dynamic or lexical ''be''), this is generally a [[stative verb]] that rarely takes the continuous aspect. See [[:Category:English stative verbs]].

